The patient, Wang X, male, 49 years old, from Nangong, Xingtai, Hebei Province, was admitted on 2022-06-01 due to right-sided limb weakness for 2 days, and altered consciousness with bradycardia for 1 day.  
Two days prior to admission, the patient presented to a local hospital due to right-sided limb weakness and was diagnosed with “acute cerebral infarction,” and received routine stroke management. One day prior, the patient developed paroxysmal twitching of the right upper limb accompanied by altered consciousness, with conjugate gaze deviation to the right; horizontal nystagmus was observed. This episode lasted for half a minute, after which consciousness recovered. There was no tongue biting, urinary or fecal incontinence, etc. ECG monitoring showed prolonged pauses, with the slowest heart rate down to 35 beats/min. Subsequently, intermittent nausea and vomiting occurred; the vomitus consisted of gastric contents. The patient came to our Emergency Department for further diagnosis and treatment.  
Non-contrast head CT in the Emergency Department showed: lacunar cerebral infarction in the right basal ganglia region; cyst in the left sphenoid sinus.  
The patient was planned for admission to the Department of Neurology for inpatient treatment; however, given the history of altered consciousness and ECG monitoring showing a slowed ventricular rate with prolonged pauses, Adams–Stokes syndrome was considered, and the patient was admitted to our department for treatment.

### Past Medical History
History of cerebral infarction more than 20 years ago, followed by several ischemic stroke episodes, with residual sequelae including left-sided limb weakness and dysarthria; history of “renal insufficiency” for 4 years, details of diagnosis and treatment unknown; history of “chronic gastritis” for several years, without specific treatment; bilateral hearing loss and severe deafness for several years; history of cholecystectomy 10 years ago.

### Personal History
Occasional smoking, details unknown; no history of alcohol abuse; no history of promiscuity.

### Marital and Reproductive History / Menstrual History
Married, with one son and one daughter; spouse and children are healthy.

### Family History
Parents are deceased, both died of “cerebral infarction”; elder brother died of “kidney disease.” Denies family history of infectious diseases and hereditary diseases.

